{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents the GLI/LigI family. GLI and LigI are both members of the functionally diverse amidohydrolase superfamily [[cite:PUB00084318]].</p>\n\n<p>GLI (also known as D-galactarolactone isomerase) catalyses the isomerisation of D-galactaro-1,5-lactone to D-galactaro-1,4-lactone [ec:5.4.1.4]]. This is a step in the oxidative degradation pathway of D-galacturonate [[cite:PUB00084318]].</p>\n\n<p>LigI (also known as 2-pyrone-4,6-dicarboxylic acid (PDC) hydrolase) hydrolyses PDC to yield 4-oxalomesaconic acid (OMA) or its tautomer, 4-carboxy-2-hydroxymuconic acid (CHM) [ec:3.1.1.57] [[cite:PUB00151269], [cite:PUB00151270]]. This reaction is part of the protocatechuate (PCA) 4,5-cleavage pathway. PCA is one of the most important intermediate metabolites in the bacterial pathways for various phenolic compounds, including lignin, which is the most abundant aromatic material in nature [[cite:PUB00114440], [cite:PUB00114441]].</p>\n\n<p>The ability of GLI to catalyse lactone isomerisation instead of hydrolysis can be explained by the absence of the general basic catalysis used by LigI [[cite:PUB00084318]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "4mup", "name" "Crystal structure of Agrobacterium tumefaciens ATU3138 (EFI target 505157), apo structure"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR032466", "name" "Metal-dependent hydrolase", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"cdd" {"cd01311" "PDC_hydrolase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "D-galactarolactone isomerase/2-pyrone-4,6-dicarbaxylate hydrolase", "short" "GLI/LigI"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 1, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 498, "taxa" 2050, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1641, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1641, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1187}, "pathways" 3}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {